\maketitle


The first results from Run 2 of the LHC experiments revealed a
hint of an unexpected feature in diphoton final state.
With integrated luminosity of $\sim 3{\mathrm{~{fb}}}^{-1}$, collected at the center-of-mass energy of $13{\mathrm{~{TeV}}}$, both CMS and ATLAS experiments
reported modest excess of two photon events over the Standard Model~(SM)
background~\cite{CMS-PAS-EXO-15-004, ATLAS-CONF-2015-081}. The global statistical significances are small. However, local significances of the excesses reach $2.6\sigma$ and $3.6\sigma$ at CMS and ATLAS, respectively, and are furthermore located in the same region of the diphoton invariant mass at $m_{\gamma\gamma} \simeq
750{\mathrm{~{GeV}}}$. The simplest theoretical interpretation of the
preliminary diphoton signal is to introduce a scalar
particle that is a singlet of the SM and along with it
additional fermionic and/or bosonic degrees of freedom that mediate 
the singlet interaction to pairs of gauge bosons. See Refs.~\cite{Knapen:2015dap,Buttazzo:2015txu,Franceschini:2015kwy} for
explicit examples.

We advocate the possibility that the SM singlet in question is a part of the $SU(5)$ symmetry breaking sector. Recall, $SU(5)$ is broken down to $SU(3) \times SU(2) \times U(1)$ through a vacuum expectation value of the SM singlet field in $24$-dimensional scalar representation~\cite{Georgi:1974sy}. The decomposition of the adjoint representation of $SU(5)$ under $SU(3) \times SU(2) \times U(1)$ is $\bm{24} \equiv \Sigma = (\bm{8},\bm{1},0) \oplus (\bm{1},\bm{3},0) \oplus (\bm{3},\bm{2},-5/6) \oplus (\overline{\bm{3}},\bm{2},5/6) \oplus (\bm{1},\bm{1},0) = (\Sigma_8, \Sigma_3, \Sigma_{3,2},\Sigma_{\overline{3},2},\Sigma_0)$. Our goal is to demonstrate that the singlet $\Sigma_0 \equiv (\bm{1},\bm{1},0)$ can reside at the electroweak scale if needed. 

